Sliding Window Technique (DSA)

The Sliding Window technique is used to efficiently solve problems involving subarrays or substrings by maintaining a "window" of elements and moving it through the data structure instead of repeatedly processing the same elements.

Why use it?

Instead of checking every subarray (which can take O(n²) time), sliding window often reduces the complexity to O(n).

It is two pointer approach in same direction

1. Fixed-Size Sliding Window

Problem: Find the maximum sum of any subarray of size k.

Example:

arr = [2, 1, 5, 1, 3, 2]
k = 3

Subarrays of size 3:
[2,1,5] → 8
[1,5,1] → 7
[5,1,3] → 9
[1,3,2] → 6

Answer = 9

When to Use Sliding Window?

Look for keywords like:

Subarray
Substring
Contiguous elements
Longest/Shortest window
Maximum/Minimum sum
At most K distinct characters
Fixed-size K window

